sentence: Howard Saul Becker (born 1928) is an American sociologist who teaches at Northwestern University.
Becker has made contributions to the sociology of deviance, sociology of art, and sociology of music.
A graduate of the University of Chicago, Becker is considered part of the second Chicago School of Sociology, which also includes Erving Goffman and Anselm Strauss.

sentence: Becker's 1963 book Outsiders is credited as one of the first books on labeling theory and its application to studies of deviance.

sentence: Becker explored the theory in which deviance is simply a social construction used to persuade the public to fear and criminalize certain groups.

sentence: A compilation of early essays on the subject, Outsiders outlines Becker's theories of deviance through two deviant groups; marijuana users and dance musicians.

sentence: In the book, Becker defines deviance as "not a quality of a bad person but the result of someone defining someone’s activity as bad.

sentence: Chapters three and four of Outsiders, which were originally published in the American Journal of Sociology in 1953, examine how marijuana users come to be labeled as social deviants.
